type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"900"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12533"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17174"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39230"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42212"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44495"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48602"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of abdominal pain, distension, and absolute constipation. Two weeks ago, she had a left knee arthroplasty and is making a steady recovery. Her medical history includes hypertension and an abdominal hysterectomy. On examination, her blood pressure is 140/90 mmHg, pulse 100/min, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is distended and soft. Digital rectal examination shows an empty rectum. The plain X-ray is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sigmoid volvulus","Pseudo-obstruction","Paralytic ileus","Caecal volvulus","Small bowel obstruction"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows a considerable volume of intestinal gas in an isolated segment of bowel. The distended gas loop is large bowel, as identified by the haustral mucosal folds. This is the classic \u0027comma sign\u0027 of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecaecal volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E. A caecal volvulus may occur where there has been a congenital incomplete dorsal mesenteric fixation of the caecum or ascending colon in association with an elongated mesentery distal to this area of absent mesentery. Caecal volvulus formation is typically seen in women in their sixties.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn a \u003Cstrong\u003Esigmoid volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E, there would be a massively dilated loop of large bowel arising out of the pelvis, with its apex in the right upper quadrant. These are typically seen in individuals (both sexes) in their 70s and are acquired secondary to chronic faecal loading.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the case of a caecal volvulus, the apex of the twisted loop is folded over into the left side of the abdominal cavity, as shown in this X-ray. \u003Cstrong\u003ESmall bowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eparalytic ileus\u003C/strong\u003E have a different mucosal pattern, with valvulae conniventes evident across the full width of the lumen of the bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith recent surgery, she may have developed a \u003Cstrong\u003Epseudo-obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E, but this usually occurs within a few days of the surgery itself. In addition, there is usually a more uniform distribution of gas throughout the colon in pseudo-obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An isolated segment of dilated colon is usually due to a volvulus."],"references":["Loo JT, Duddalwar V, Chen FK, et al. Abdominal radiograph pearls and pitfalls for the emergency department radiologist: a pictorial review. Abdom Radiol 2017; 42:987-1019. Available online: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27503382/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33531"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1066"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16849"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16849"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f6212b59-f8c9-400b-b311-13577da29748.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f6212b59-f8c9-400b-b311-13577da29748.jpg","isProcessed"